{"questionId":"35019863","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Three towns, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> are represented as coordinates on a map, where the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math> axes&nbsp;represent the distances east and north of an origin, respectively, measured in kilometres.</p>\n<p>Town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> is located at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math> is located at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo></math>. A road runs along the perpendicular bisector of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>[AB]</mtext></math>. This information is shown in the following diagram.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/e986c831b89c7842615793ee6feecb63a0f14d9d.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> is due north of town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math> and the road passes through town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math>.</p>\n<p>Find the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi></math>-coordinate of town <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>substituting&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></math>&nbsp;into their equation from part (a)&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>9</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>M1A0</strong></em> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>16</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math> as their final answer.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35019863","referenceCode":"22M.1.SL.TZ1.4b","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Town C is due north of town A and the road passes through town C. Find the y-coordinate of town C.","paper":"1","level":"SL","questionNumber":"b","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 2—Functions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.5—Intersection of lines, equations of perpendicular bisectors","Topic 2—Functions","SL 2.1—Equations of straight lines, parallel and perpendicular"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}